      "date": "2026-01-23 17:31:10.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nI attempted to fix the build errors present in this patch and succeeded. Yay! Now, keep in mind I barely have any idea what I am doing, so please doublecheck the changes I made to make sure they make sense.\n\nThis service is only provided in hopes to be useful and reduce latency from push to getting actual results in the face of trivial code errors\n\nHere's summary of my changes:\nExcellent! The fix has been applied successfully.\n\n## Summary\n\n**The Fix:**\nI fixed the compile error by modifying the `strncpy` call in the `lustre_lnet_set_ni_state` function at line 2840 of `lnet/utils/lnetconfig/liblnetconfig.c`.\n\n**What was changed:**\n- Changed `strncpy(data.cfg_config_u.cfg_net.net_intf, intf, LNET_MAX_STR_LEN)` to `strncpy(data.cfg_config_u.cfg_net.net_intf, intf, LNET_MAX_STR_LEN - 1)`\n- Added explicit null-termination: `data.cfg_config_u.cfg_net.net_intf[LNET_MAX_STR_LEN - 1] = '\\0'`\n\n**Rationale:**\nThe compiler error `-Werror=stringop-truncation` was triggered because `strncpy` was called with a size parameter (`LNET_MAX_STR_LEN`) that equals the destination buffer size. This is problematic because:\n\n1. If the source string (`intf`) is >= `LNET_MAX_STR_LEN` bytes, `strncpy` will copy exactly `LNET_MAX_STR_LEN` bytes without adding a null terminator\n2. This leaves the destination buffer without proper null-termination, which can lead to buffer overruns when the string is later used\n\nThe fix ensures:\n1. At most `LNET_MAX_STR_LEN - 1` characters are copied from the source\n2. The last byte of the buffer is explicitly set to `'\\0'`, guaranteeing null-termination\n3. This prevents potential buffer overflow issues and satisfies the compiler's stringop-truncation warning\n\nThis is a standard defensive programming practice when using `strncpy` to ensure strings are always properly null-terminated.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
